## Template System

### Template Structure

OSINT templates are YAML files defining reusable intelligence gathering configurations.

**Example: Twitter Monitoring Template**

```yaml
name: "Twitter Account Monitoring"
category: "social_media"
description: "Monitor Twitter/X accounts for activity patterns and content"
version: "1.0"
author: "OSINT Service"

parameters:
  - name: username
    type: string
    required: true
    description: "Twitter username to monitor"

  - name: monitor_followers
    type: boolean
    default: true
    description: "Track follower count changes"

  - name: track_hashtags
    type: array
    default: []
    description: "Hashtags to monitor in user's tweets"

sources:
  - name: twitter_profile
    url: "https://twitter.com/{username}"
    method: GET
    rate_limit: 100

  - name: twitter_api
    url: "https://api.twitter.com/2/users/by/username/{username}"
    method: GET
    auth_required: true
    rate_limit: 300

metrics:
  - name: follower_count
    type: integer
    anomaly_detection: true

  - name: following_count
    type: integer
    anomaly_detection: true

  - name: tweet_frequency
    type: float
    anomaly_detection: true
    unit: "tweets_per_day"

alerts:
  - condition: "follower_count_change > 1000"
    level: warning
    message: "Significant follower count change detected"

  - condition: "tweet_frequency > avg * 3"
    level: info
    message: "Unusually high tweet activity"

schedule:
  interval: "1h"
  max_failures: 3
```

### Template Categories

| Category | Count | Description |
|----------|-------|-------------|
| `social_media` | 11 | Twitter, LinkedIn, Facebook, Instagram, Reddit, YouTube, TikTok, Telegram, GitHub, Discord, StackOverflow |
| `threat_intelligence` | 7 | Malware hashes, IP reputation, CVE monitoring, phishing, ransomware, botnets, exploits |
| `domain_analysis` | 8 | WHOIS, DNS, SSL certificates, website changes, tech stack, subdomains, backlinks, robots.txt, sitemaps |
| `data_breach` | 4 | HaveIBeenPwned, credential leaks, database leaks, password breaches |
